<subSubSection id="FDB4935E024213378D40038A55D28AF5" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="5EEEDBB154140A2CBEEB452A3FF68EF1" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="292DA34E12A2F0581D19BFADFD2E655D" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
<taxonomicName id="F948A1F36C4384676FB954B0CE89B5AB" authorityName="Mendes &amp; Andersen" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Nilothauma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilothauma amazonense" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonense">
<emphasis id="90B32097D4AF9ACB3231A77651AC11DD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Nilothauma amazonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Mendes &amp; Andersen, 2009 was described, based on a single male from the Amazon. The specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4411EC45E1F4D17250D3889E18F8889A" genus="N." lsidName="N. amazonense" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="amazonense">
<emphasis id="3E356FE302A13F25589DFC559A54A42C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">N. amazonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from southern Brazil, however, differ slightly from the holotype. 
<bibRefCitation id="7333A34B66B095E8E06F3F4A1016FF40" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" author="Mendes, HF" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B8" refString="Mendes, HF, Andersen, T, 2009. Neotropical Nilothauma Kieffer, 1921, with the description of thirteen new species (Diptera: Chironomidae). Zootaxa 2063: 1 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" title="Neotropical Nilothauma Kieffer, 1921, with the description of thirteen new species (Diptera: Chironomidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" volume="2063" year="2009">Mendes and Andersen (2009)</bibRefCitation>
stated that hind ta2 being shorter than ta3 (ratio of ta2/ta3 length = 0.73) is one of the diagnostic characters of the species. However, in the specimens from southern Brazil, hind ta2 and ta3 are subequal in length (ratio of ta2/ta3 length = 0.94-0.97). Body size, measured as Total Length (TL) is also larger (TL of holotype = 1.53 mm; TL of southern populations = 2.00-2.05 mm). Similar differences in body size between Amazonian and southern Atlantic Forest populations were also found in 
<taxonomicName id="BADC6703E5A93013E1EE1F2B357D8237" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Beardius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Beardius urupeatan" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="urupeatan">
<emphasis id="3180A2511A7A7EE180B15C7FE2FC11C6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Beardius urupeatan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Pinho, Mendes &amp; Andersen, 2009 [TL Amazon = 2.32-2.51, 2.38 (6); TL southern Atlantic Forest = 2.68-3.00, 2.96 (8)]. This intraspecific variation might be due to the higher temperature in the Amazon Region when compared to the localities in the southern parts of the Atlantic Forest. Populations of chironomid species inhabiting different habitats may show variation in voltinism and more rapid growth can result in smaller body size (
<bibRefCitation id="DCFFF0FEE5DC8E0510EDE5F855DCB954" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-94-011-0715-0_10" author="Tokeshi, M" editor="Armitage, PD" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" pagination="225 - 268" refId="B17" refString="Tokeshi, M, 1995. Life cycles and population dynamics. In: Armitage, PD, Cranston, PS, Pinder, LCV, Eds., The Chironomidae: Biology and ecology of non-biting midges. Chapman &amp; Hall, London: 225 - 268, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/978-94-011-0715-0_10" title="Life cycles and population dynamics." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-94-011-0715-0_10" volumeTitle="The Chironomidae: Biology and ecology of non-biting midges." year="1995">Tokeshi 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="295A66BD1FC830684DBCA7946068D565" author="Pinho, LC" journalOrPublisher="Spixiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" pagination="255 - 264" refId="B10" refString="Pinho, LC, Mendes, HF, Andersen, T, 2009. New species and records of Beardius Reiss &amp; Sublette from Brazil (Diptera, Chironomidae). Spixiana 32: 255 - 264" title="New species and records of Beardius Reiss &amp; Sublette from Brazil (Diptera, Chironomidae)." volume="32" year="2009">Pinho et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AAF51561411B70EC85B143E89B4FA894" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="01C76D82A1A2457925CDB5E2CA5FA62F" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="13246BD619D6CAF2D76EA5F2C5B52DB6" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="49C9A89A443760D2CDAEE8C2ADA337F3" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A4455A78D40166704C5934F53EAB0639" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Distribution maps of Neotropical Nilothauma species A N. fittkaui (Soponis, 1987), N. amazonense Mendes &amp; Andersen, 2009 B N. aripuanense Mendes &amp; Andersen, 2009, N Nilothauma aleta Roback, 1960 C N. reissi (Soponis, 1987), N. soka Andersen, Bello-Gonzalez &amp; Hagenlund, 2016 D N. anamariae Dantas &amp; Hamada, 2017, N. jaraguaense Mendes &amp; Andersen, 2009." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1033.60686.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/534710" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">17A</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
The species was originally described from the Amazonian Region by 
<bibRefCitation id="C66FDC11E5824982EECB203EE471B96F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" author="Mendes, HF" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B8" refString="Mendes, HF, Andersen, T, 2009. Neotropical Nilothauma Kieffer, 1921, with the description of thirteen new species (Diptera: Chironomidae). Zootaxa 2063: 1 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" title="Neotropical Nilothauma Kieffer, 1921, with the description of thirteen new species (Diptera: Chironomidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" volume="2063" year="2009">Mendes and Andersen (2009)</bibRefCitation>
; the range is now extended to Santa Catarina State in southern Brazil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
